In Java, it is not possible to simultaneously read and write to the same file with a single stream. However, you can achieve the desired functionality by using two separate streams—one for reading from the file and another for writing to the file. Here's an example:

```java
import java.io.*;

public class ReadWriteFile {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String filename = "example.txt";

        try {
            // Open the file for reading
            FileInputStream inputStream = new FileInputStream(filename);
            BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(inputStream));

            // Open the file for writing
            FileWriter writer = new FileWriter(filename, true); // 'true' indicates append mode, change it as needed
            BufferedWriter bufferedWriter = new BufferedWriter(writer);

            // Read from the file
            String line;
            while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
                // Process the read line if needed
                System.out.println("Read: " + line);

                // Write to the file (for example, write the same line back)
                bufferedWriter.write(line);
                bufferedWriter.newLine();
                bufferedWriter.flush();
            }

            // Close the streams
            inputStream.close();
            reader.close();
            bufferedWriter.close();
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the program opens a file (`example.txt`) for reading using a `FileInputStream` and `BufferedReader`. It then opens the same file for writing using a `FileWriter` and `BufferedWriter`. It then reads each line from the file, processes it if needed, and writes it back to the file. Finally, it closes the streams to release system resources.

Note that while the example reads and writes to the same file, it is done sequentially rather than simultaneously.

Apologies for the confusion. If you want to read from and write to a Win32 serial communication device (such as `"\\.\COM5"`), you cannot achieve it with file I/O operations since it requires specific serial communication libraries. In Java, you need to use a library like RXTX or jSerialComm to handle direct communication with the serial port.

Here's an example using the jSerialComm library:

```java
import com.fazecast.jSerialComm.*;

public class ReadWriteSerial {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SerialPort port = SerialPort.getCommPort("COM5");
        port.setComPortParameters(9600, 8, 1, 0); // Configure the port settings
        port.openPort(); // Open the serial port

        // Create a separate thread for reading from the serial port
        Thread readThread = new Thread(() -> {
            try {
                byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
                while (true) {
                    int numRead = port.readBytes(buffer, buffer.length);
                    if (numRead > 0) {
                        String receivedData = new String(buffer, 0, numRead);
                        System.out.println("Received: " + receivedData);
                    }
                    Thread.sleep(1);
                }
            } catch (Exception e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
        });
        readThread.start();

        // Send data to the serial port from the main thread
        try {
            String sendData = "Hello from Java!";
            port.writeBytes(sendData.getBytes(), sendData.length());
            System.out.println("Sent: " + sendData);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        // Close the serial port
        port.closePort();
    }
}
```

In this example, we use the jSerialComm library to open the `"COM5"` serial port and configure its parameters. We create a separate thread to continuously read from the port and print the received data. In the main thread, we send data to the port.

Please note that for this code to work, you need to have the jSerialComm library included in your project or build path. You can obtain it from the official website or Maven repository.

